Title: Viewing shape through distorting media  
Author: Kevin Arthur 
Date: December 12, 1994  
Abstract: The manifold of light rays that reach the retina to form an image do not typically span the viewing sphere uniformly. Light reflects or refracts off of surfaces to form folds in the spherical image of the ray manifold, referred to as optical caustics. These caustics determine the topology of the images of points and curves in object space. This report describes how the geometry of points and curves changes on encountering caustics in the ray manifold, and applies these concepts to some geometrically interesting phenomena that occur in nature: mirages, refraction through water droplets, and reflection off of rippling water.
