Reference-contexts: Multiple imaging happens when we see both an object and its reflection in a mirror, for example. The spherical image of the ray propagation develops folds and pleats. Generally, a fold line signifies a place where the light rays focus and change direction. These lines form optical caustics <ref> [Berry and Upstill, 1980] </ref>. The caustics divide up the spherical image into regions where different number of rays reach a point in the scene. When light hits a surface and reflects or refracts, caustics can occur, intersecting the parabolic curves on the surface. <p> A star in the sky, for example, may be seen in two places at the same time through a telescope because of gravitational refraction by planets or galaxies. Generally, the number of image points that we see from a single object point must be odd <ref> [Berry and Upstill, 1980] </ref>. Multiple imaging of points is well understood and has long been a subject of study for astronomers. Recently, Berry [1987] has described the effect of optical caustics on the imaging of curves. <p> One typically views the caustics in the far field by watching the light patterns refracted onto a wall a meter or so away, or one can view the caustics at multiple depths in the near field to see their three-dimensional structure and their formation <ref> [Berry and Upstill, 1980] </ref>[Lock and Andrews, 1992]. We first consider a droplet sitting flat on a horizontal transparent surface. In this case the tension on the surface of the drop is relatively uniform (in particular, gravity acts uniformly on the droplet).
